 focuses on three main areas of Rengger’s contribution to the political theory of international relations: his Augustine-inspired idea of an ‘Anti-Pelagian Imagination’; his Oakeshottian argument for a pluralist ‘conversation of mankind’; and his ruminations on war as the uncivil condition in world politics. Through a critical engagement with his work, the book illuminates the promises and limitations of civility as a sceptical, non-utopian, anti-perfectionist approach to theorizing world order that transcends both realist pessimism and liberal utopianism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDingli, Sophia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy-Pipe, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Anthony F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorkevičius, Valerie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Sullivan, Noël, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaipais, Vassilios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaipais, Vassilios, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchick, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValk, John-Harmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhatmore, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Michael C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Comp